  <h2>Understanding Wine With Salmon</h2>
  <p>When it comes to wine with salmon, quality matters more than price. Our team of sommeliers has tasted hundreds of options to bring you these expert recommendations.</p>

  <h2>Perfect Food Pairings</h2>

<h3 class="text-wine-700">Why Salmon and Wine Create Magic</h3>
<p>Salmon's rich, oily texture and delicate flavor profile make it one of the most wine-friendly proteins. The fish's natural oils require wines with sufficient acidity to cleanse the palate, while its meaty texture can handle both light reds and fuller-bodied whites. The key lies in salmon's moderate fat content—roughly 13 grams per 100g—which needs acidic wines to cut through richness without overwhelming the fish's subtle sweetness. Additionally, salmon's umami compounds, particularly inosinate, create savory depth that pairs beautifully with wines showing minerality and complexity.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700">Classic Pairings That Never Fail</h3>
<p>The gold standard remains <strong>Pinot Noir from Burgundy or Oregon</strong> with simply grilled salmon. The wine's bright acidity (typically 6-7 g/L) cuts through the fish's oils, while its earthy undertones complement salmon's natural flavors without masking them. <strong>Chardonnay from Chablis</strong> offers another timeless match—the wine's steely minerality and crisp acidity (often 7-8 g/L) enhance salmon's delicate taste, while subtle oak aging adds complementary richness.</p>

<p><strong>Champagne and smoked salmon</strong> represents perhaps the most celebrated pairing. The wine's effervescence and high acidity (8-9 g/L) cleanse the palate between bites of rich, smoky fish, while the yeast-derived flavors from lees aging echo the complex, cured characteristics of properly smoked salmon.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700">Modern Creative Combinations</h3>
<p>Contemporary chefs are exploring exciting new territories. <strong>Grüner Veltliner</strong> with Asian-spiced salmon showcases the grape's peppery notes and zesty acidity against ginger and soy-based preparations. <strong>Albariño from Rías Baixas</strong> brings saline minerality that mirrors the ocean origins of both wine and fish, particularly stunning with salmon tartare dressed in citrus.</p>

<p><strong>Natural wines</strong> offer intriguing possibilities—a skin-contact Pinot Grigio from Friuli provides textural complexity and orange-wine tannins that complement salmon's protein structure, while maintaining the acidity needed for the pairing to succeed.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700">Cooking Methods Transform Pairings</h3>
<p><strong>Grilled salmon</strong> develops smoky, caramelized notes that call for wines with more structure—try Syrah from Northern Rhône or Sangiovese from Chianti Classico. The char and grill marks add bitter compounds that harmonize with moderate tannins.</p>

<p><strong>Poached or steamed salmon</strong> retains maximum delicacy, pairing beautifully with <strong>Sancerre or Muscadet</strong>—wines that won't overpower the subtle preparation. <strong>Cedar-plank salmon</strong> gains woody aromatics that echo oak-aged wines like Rioja Reserva or barrel-aged Chenin Blanc from Loire Valley.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700">Sauce and Seasoning Considerations</h3>
<p><strong>Hollandaise or butter-based sauces</strong> demand wines with cutting acidity—German Riesling Kabinett or Sancerre work brilliantly. <strong>Dill and lemon preparations</strong> shine with Sauvignon Blanc, whose herbaceous qualities and citrusy brightness mirror the seasonings perfectly.</p>

<p><strong>Teriyaki-glazed salmon</strong> needs wines that handle sweetness—off-dry Riesling from Alsace or Gewürztraminer provide aromatic intensity and slight residual sugar to balance soy and mirin.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700">Pairings to Avoid</h3>
<p>High-tannin reds like Cabernet Sauvignon create metallic, bitter interactions with salmon's oils. Heavy, oaked Chardonnays can overwhelm delicate fish preparations, while very dry, austere wines like Muscadet Sur Lie might seem thin against rich salmon dishes.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700">Regional Authenticity</h3>
<p>Honor traditional pairings: <strong>Norwegian gravlax with aquavit-washed Burgundian Chardonnay</strong>, or <strong>Scottish smoked salmon with Islay whisky-barrel-aged wines</strong>. These regional connections respect both ingredients' origins while creating harmonious flavor bridges.</p>

