<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Match Wine Body to Salmon Preparation Method</strong> - Wild salmon's leaner texture pairs beautifully with medium-bodied wines like Burgundian Chardonnay or Loire Valley Sancerre, while rich farmed Atlantic salmon can handle fuller-bodied wines like Viognier or even light Pinot Noir. The key is matching the wine's weight to the fish's oil content—lean King salmon calls for crisp Chablis, while buttery Coho salmon shines with oaked Chardonnay.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve White Wines Slightly Warmer Than Usual</strong> - Pour white wines at 50-55°F instead of the typical 45°F when pairing with salmon. This higher temperature allows the wine's texture and mid-palate richness to complement the fish's natural oils without being overwhelmed by excessive acidity. This is particularly crucial for Chardonnay and white Rhône blends.</li>

  <li><strong>Consider Salmon's Natural Astaxanthin When Choosing Reds</strong> - The carotenoid that gives salmon its pink color creates subtle earthy, almost mineral notes that pair exceptionally with Pinot Noir's forest floor characteristics. Oregon Pinot Noir, with its higher natural acidity and lower tannins, complements this compound better than heavier reds that would mask these delicate flavor interactions.</li>

  <li><strong>Decant Mature Burgundy Even for Salmon</strong> - Unlike typical fish pairings where you'd avoid decanting, aged red Burgundy (8+ years) benefits from 30 minutes of decanting before serving with salmon. The gentle aeration softens any remaining tannins and allows the wine's secondary mushroom and earth notes to emerge, creating a bridge between the wine's terroir and salmon's umami richness.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose Burgundy Glasses for Both Red and White</strong> - The wider bowl of a Burgundy glass concentrates both the wine's aromatics and the salmon's natural oils on your palate simultaneously. This is especially important for complex pairings like cedar plank salmon with aged Chassagne-Montrachet, where you want both the wine's mineral backbone and the fish's smoky elements to integrate properly.</li>

  <li><strong>Time Young Champagne Service to Salmon's Temperature</strong> - Serve salmon at room temperature (not chilled) when pairing with young, high-acidity Champagne or Crémant. The contrast between the cool, effervescent wine and the fish's natural oils creates a palate-cleansing effect that enhances both elements. This technique works particularly well with gravlax or sashimi-grade salmon.</li>

  <li><strong>Avoid Wines Over 10 Years Old with Grilled Salmon</strong> - The char and smoke from grilling can overpower the delicate tertiary flavors in aged wines. Instead, choose wines 3-7 years old that still retain primary fruit characteristics but have developed enough complexity to stand up to the Maillard reaction compounds. A 5-year-old Sancerre or 4-year-old Oregon Pinot Noir hits this sweet spot perfectly.</li>

  <li><strong>Account for Salmon's Seasonal Fat Content</strong> - Wild salmon caught during spawning runs (late summer/fall) has higher fat content and requires wines with more acidity to cut through the richness. Choose Muscadet or Albariño for fatty fall salmon, while leaner spring salmon pairs better with softer wines like white Burgundy or Alsatian Pinot Blanc.</li>
</ol>



