  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when choosing wine for salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is choosing wines that are too heavy or tannic, which overwhelm salmon's delicate flavor. Full-bodied Cabernet Sauvignon or heavily oaked Chardonnay can mask the fish entirely. Another frequent error is ignoring the cooking method and sauce—grilled salmon with hollandaise needs a different wine than poached salmon with herbs.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can you pair sparkling wine with salmon dishes?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sparkling wines are excellent with salmon, especially for richer preparations like salmon with cream sauce or smoked salmon appetizers. Champagne, Cava, or Prosecco's bubbles and acidity cleanse the palate between bites while complementing the fish's oils. Choose Blanc de Blancs for delicate preparations or rosé Champagne for heartier salmon dishes.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How does salmon preparation method change the wine pairing?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Cooking method dramatically affects wine choice because it changes the salmon's texture and flavor intensity. Poached salmon's delicate nature calls for light whites like Albariño, while blackened salmon's bold spices can handle robust wines like Côtes du Rhône. Grilled salmon develops caramelized notes that pair beautifully with lightly oaked wines, and raw preparations like sashimi need high-acid wines like Muscadet.</p>
  </div>

